title: A Multi-centre, Double-blind, Parallel-group, Randomised Controlled Study to Investigate Efficacy, Safety and Tolerability of Orally Administered BI 409306 During a 12-week Treatment Period Compared to Placebo in Patients With Cognitive Impairment Due to Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief: The study is designed to compare the effects of BI 409306 compared to placebo in patients with cognitive impairment due to Alzheimer's Disease

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: All patients were screened for eligibility. All patients eligible after screening underwent a 2-week single-blind placebo run-in period before randomisation. Patients were not to be randomized to trial treatment if any one of the specific entry criteria were not met.
participantFlowModule.recruitmentDetails: This was a Phase II, multi-centre, double-blind, parallel-group, randomised, placebo controlled trial with patients with mild Alzheimer's disease. The randomisation allocation ratio was 1:1:1:1:2 of 10 milligram (mg), 25 mg, 50 mg once daily (QD), 25 mg twice a day (BID) of BI 409306 and placebo respectively.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Neuropsychological Test Battery in Total Z-score After 12-week Treatment.
outcomeMeasures.description: Neuropsychological Test Battery (NTB) response, defined as change from baseline in total z-score after 12 weeks of treatment. The NTB consists of 9 validated components. Raw scores on each of the 9 NTB tests were converted to z-scores using the baseline means and standard deviations (SDs) for each test. The resultant z-scores were averaged to obtain a total z-score, incorporating all 9 NTB tests. The NTB Z-score indicates the number of standard deviations away from the mean. A Z-score of 0 is equal to the mean at baseline. Negative numbers indicate values lower than baseline and positive numbers indicate values higher than baseline. Least Squares Mean is actually an adjusted mean change from baseline.

outcomeMeasures.description: Neuropsychological Test Battery (NTB) response, defined as change from baseline in total z-score after 12 weeks of treatment. The NTB consists of 9 validated components. Raw scores on each of the 9 NTB tests were converted to z-scores using the baseline means and standard deviations (SDs) for each test. The resultant z-scores were averaged to obtain a total z-score, incorporating all 9 NTB tests. The NTB Z-score indicates the number of standard deviations away from the mean. A Z-score of 0 is equal to the mean at baseline. Negative numbers indicate values lower than baseline and positive numbers indicate values higher than baseline. outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Alzheimer's Disease Cooperative Study/Activities of Daily Living (ADCS-ADL) Total Score After 12-week Treatment
outcomeMeasures.description: Alzheimer's Disease Cooperative Study/Activities of Daily Living (ADCS-ADL) is a rating scale used to assess basic and instrumental activities of daily living. In the full version of the scale, 23 items are rated by the investigator using information supplied by the caregiver. Each item has a score range varying from 0-3 to 0-5. The sum score can range from 0 to 78. Higher scores indicate better function. Least Squares Mean is actually an adjusted mean change from baseline.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Clinical Dementia Rating Scale Sum of Boxes (CDR-SB) Total Score After 12-week Treatment
outcomeMeasures.description: The CDR-SB is obtained through semi-structured interviews of patients and informants, and cognitive functioning was rated in 6 domains of functioning: memory, orientation, judgment and problem solving, community affairs, home and hobbies and personal care. Each domain was rated on a 5-point scale of functioning as follows: 0-no impairment; 0.5-questionable impairment; 1-mild impairment; 2-moderate impairment and 3-severe impairment. Only personal care was scored on a 4-point scale without a 0.5 rating available. The higher the score, the greater the severity of dementia. Least Squares Mean is actually an adjusted mean change from baseline.

drug: BI 409306 (oral small-molecule phosphodiesterase 9A [PDE9A] inhibitor; intended as a symptomatic cognitive treatment)
explanation_target: Reason: The trial tests BI 409306, an orally administered small molecule that selectively inhibits phosphodiesterase 9A (PDE9A). PDE9A inhibition raises cGMP with the goal of improving synaptic signalling and cognition rather than directly removing amyloid or tau pathology, so the mechanism and intended effect are symptomatic cognitive enhancement. citeturn0search0turn0search1

Act: Key trial details — multicentre, double-blind, parallel-group RCT of oral BI 409306 vs placebo for 12 weeks in patients with cognitive impairment due to Alzheimer’s disease; primary endpoints were cognitive measures (e.g., Neuropsychological Test Battery). BI 409306 is described in the literature and clinicaltrials reports as a PDE9A inhibitor developed for cognitive improvement. citeturn0search1turn0search2

Additional supporting evidence: Phase I/II publications describe BI 409306 as a potent, selective PDE9A inhibitor that increases CSF cGMP and was tested for cognitive outcomes in AD and schizophrenia. The pooled phase II analysis reported no cognitive benefit over placebo, though the compound was generally well tolerated. citeturn0search0turn0search2turn0search5

Reflect: Classification rationale — This is not a biologic (no monoclonal antibody or vaccine) and does not target core AD pathology (amyloid or tau) directly, so it does not meet the definitions for 'disease-targeted biologic' or 'disease-targeted small molecule.' Instead it is a small-molecule, symptomatic cognitive enhancer acting via PDE9A inhibition; therefore 'cognitive enhancer' is the appropriate category. No significant ambiguity remains given the clear mechanism and trial endpoints. citeturn0search2turn0search1
explanation_agent: Reason: BI 409306 is an oral small-molecule inhibitor of phosphodiesterase 9A (PDE9A) that raises cGMP and is intended to strengthen NMDA receptor–related signalling, long-term potentiation and synaptic plasticity to improve cognition (a symptomatic cognitive-enhancer mechanism rather than direct anti-amyloid or anti-tau disease modification). citeturn0search4turn0search2

Act: Key trial details and drug mechanism — multicentre, double-blind, parallel-group RCTs of BI 409306 (10–50 mg daily for 12 weeks) in prodromal/mild AD used cognitive batteries (NTB, CDR-SB, ADAS-Cog) as primary/secondary endpoints; BI 409306 is described in the literature and phase I studies as a selective PDE9A inhibitor that increases CSF cGMP. These facts point to a synaptic-plasticity / neuroprotection symptomatic strategy rather than amyloid/tau, inflammation, or vascular targeting. citeturn0search1turn0search2

Reflect: The mechanism (PDE9A inhibition → increased cGMP → enhanced LTP/synaptic signalling) maps directly to CADRO category M (Synaptic Plasticity/Neuroprotection). The trial targets symptomatic cognitive enhancement through synaptic function, with no evidence of amyloid-, tau-, ApoE- or inflammation-directed disease modification; therefore M is the most specific fit. citeturn0search4
- Phase II pooled analyses and full-text description of the two phase II RCTs in prodromal and mild AD (BI 409306; cognitive endpoints; no clinical benefit observed). citeturn0search1turn0search4
- Phase I proof-of-mechanism study showing BI 409306 increases CSF cGMP (pharmacodynamic evidence supporting synaptic/cGMP mechanism). citeturn0search2
- Phase II trial in schizophrenia describing BI 409306 as a selective PDE9 inhibitor and reporting cognitive outcome data and safety. citeturn0search0
